Patch Set 1:

(3 comments)

This is at best incomplete (missing to remove further test code, e.g. pdf2xml.cxx), or a misunderstanding.

It is true that this code is effectively dead since the gbuild migration (sadly). If it _should_ get converted into modern-day unit tests, then _both_ pdf and xml files (as well as the *_out.def files) should be retained.

Patch Set 1:

> If it _should_ get converted into modern-day unit tests, then _both_ pdf and xml files (as well as the *_out.def files) should be retained.

I understand that those xml files and *_out.def files are originally used to do diff tests. However, in my opinion this kind of test is meaningless.

Assume I have developed an application to generate an xml file. Originally the generated xml looks like this:
    <xml>
        <node1>a</node1>
        <node2>b</node2>
    </xml>

So what the diff test does is to include the whole output of the xml in the code base, and compare the re-generated xml during each test run against the pre-generated xml. This means that any modification to the code base should not change any part of the xml, otherwise the unit test would fail.

Oh? Why not?? For instance, if I changed the source code so that the generated xml would now look like this (i.e., having the new-line characters removed):
    <xml><node1>a</node1><node2>b</node2></xml>

Or, if I updated the code to add an attribute to on of the nodes:
    <xml><node1 name="test">a</node1><node2>b</node2></xml>

Or these modification would cause the unit test to fail, even though the generated xml files are all valid xml files. From this point of view, the original unit test case would have the meaning that "DO NOT MODIFY MY CODE". Or, to let the unit test pass, the one who modified the code need to update the pre-generated xml file each time the output structure is changed.

The same logic applies to those .def files. For instance, if I modified the code to let the following xpdf output:
    updateFont 21 1 0 0 0 1400.000000 11128 BAAAAA+DejaVuSerif
be changed to:
    updateFont 21 1 0 0 0 1400.00 11128 "DejaVuSerif"
Then I need to re-generate those .def files, add and commit to git and upload to gerrit.

It would be OK if there is only one or two of those pre-generated files, but what if there are many (like the case in sdext/source/pdfimport/test/testdocs)? What if those files are extremely large (e.g. the one in xpdftest which is 75MB)? Any modification to the code would require the contributor to update the pre-generated xml and .def files and transmit them onto gerrit for review; the one who reviews it would need to download them.... Also I heard there is a hook in our git to limit the file upload size, thus any such attempt would fail nowadays. And, the checked-out core code (without submodules) is 1GB so these 81MB is 8% of the size.

The correct way to test the functionality of the code is like the one in commit 12b57e4. Using an xml parser, you check the existence of a certain node or attribute. If a certain node or attribute should not be there, you can also assert it. 

For those .def files, you can assert the existence of a certain line as well as the value of at a certain position within that line. But you simply should not diff each line. Actually the text_1_out.def is generated from the 20 page book.pdf, and there are many repeated xpdf output lines in the text_1_out.def which do the same thing. In addition, the binary_1_out.def actually includes the binary stream generated from the book.pdf, which include the font streams, toUnicode map streams etc. They are saved in the def file, but the only thing we want to check is to see if the run-time generated staff is exactly the same as the def file??

Patch Set 1:

> So what the diff test does is to include the whole output of the xml in the code base, and compare the re-generated xml during each test run against the pre-generated xml. This means that any modification to the code base should not change any part of the xml, otherwise the unit test would fail.
> 

Well, the code involved in generating that xml is pretty small (modulo poppler). So yes, it is not a unit test, but an integration test. For that, it did exactly what you want - trip up if _anything_ changes, so you as a developer can inspect it.

Note that updating unit tests after further bugfixing is mostly business as usual.

It also appears those tests did work without modifications from 2008 to 2011.

> It would be OK if there is only one or two of those pre-generated files, but what if there are many (like the case in sdext/source/pdfimport/test/testdocs)? What if those files are extremely large (e.g. the one in xpdftest which is 75MB)? Any modification to the code would require the contributor to update the pre-generated xml and .def files and transmit them onto gerrit for review; the one who reviews it would need to download them.... Also I heard there is a hook in our git to limit the file upload size, thus any such attempt would fail nowadays. And, the checked-out core code (without submodules) is 1GB so these 81MB is 8% of the size.
> 

Yes, the size problem is a fair point.

> The correct way to test the functionality of the code is like the one in commit 12b57e4. Using an xml parser, you check the existence of a certain node or attribute. If a certain node or attribute should not be there, you can also assert it. 
> 

That is a lot of work, and if you want to have full coverage, will likely not result in tests that need _less_ modifications after code changes. Note further that your examples above (linefeeds, font names) could easily be normalized before diffing.

I didn't put -1 here on purpose, this is mostly discussing how to best move forward. Covering as large a space as PDF with unit tests is a lot of work, vs. taking what is there & making it work again. On the details (where files sit) - we have the crash testing & export compatibility regression testing framework, where we keep known-good & reference files outside the core repo (and don't burden developer machines with running it). Perhaps that is the right place to put those large test files, too? Then I'd also remove the pdf files here, though.
